<$transclude $tiddler="$:/plugins/rimir/doc-template/templates/page">
<$fill $name="body">

!! The body-cascade swap

A dashboard is an ordinary tiddler tagged <<tag "$:/tags/rimir/dashboard">>. The plugin ships a `ViewTemplateBodyFilter` step, `$:/config/ViewTemplateBodyFilters/rimir-dashboard`, ordered `list-before` the `default` step:

```
[tag[$:/tags/rimir/dashboard]then[$:/plugins/rimir/dashboard/body]]
```

So when a dashboard tiddler is viewed, its body renders `$:/plugins/rimir/dashboard/body` — the canvas — while its title, tags and fields render through the normal ViewTemplate. Nothing else about the tiddler is special.

!! Tiles are tiddlers

Each tile is its own tiddler tagged <<tag "$:/tags/rimir/dashboard/tile">>, stored under a system-tiddler prefix:

```
$:/config/rimir/dashboard/<dashId>/tiles/<uid>
```

`<dashId>` is the dashboard's `dashboard-id` field (auto-generated for dashboards made with the //New dashboard// button) or, as a fallback, the dashboard's title. Tiles carry plain fields — `dashboard`, `target`, `x`, `y`, `w`, `h`, `z`, `style` — so every operation is a plain `$action-createtiddler` / `$action-setfield` / `$action-deletetiddler`. There is no JSON serialisation to parse or rebuild, and the compact numeric fields keep the tiddlers in single-file `.tid` form.

The canvas enumerates its tiles with:

```
[all[tiddlers]tag[$:/tags/rimir/dashboard/tile]field:dashboard<dashId>nsort[z]]
```

Rendering in `z` order means DOM order and `z-index` agree.

!! The `<$dashboard-drag>` widget

Free-form pointer dragging is the one thing wikitext cannot express, so a single JS widget owns it. It renders an absolutely-positioned box from `x`/`y`/`w`/`h`/`z` attributes and handles pointer interaction:

* ''move'' starts on a `.rr-dash-handle` descendant (window tiles) or anywhere on the box when `move-selector` is empty (bare tiles);
* ''resize'' starts on a `.rr-dash-resize` descendant;
* elements marked `.rr-dash-no-drag` (buttons, the controls cluster) never start a drag.

During a drag the DOM node is moved directly for smoothness. The geometry is written back exactly once, on pointer release, by invoking the `actions` string — a plain `$action-setfield` on the tile tiddler. Committing on release rather than on every pointermove avoids the async write races that come from saving on each interaction event.

A pointerdown+up with no motion beyond a small threshold is treated as a ''click'' and invokes `open-actions` instead (used to navigate the target into the story river). Move and resize commits also recompute `z = max(sibling z) + 1`, giving bring-to-front behaviour.

!! The contents popup

The ⧉ tile control writes the target's title into `$:/state/rimir/dashboard/popup`. A single `<$reveal>` — rendered once at the canvas root, not per tile — watches that state and, when it is non-empty, shows a fixed-position overlay containing the target rendered through the default `$:/core/ui/ViewTemplate`:

```
<$tiddler tiddler={{$:/state/rimir/dashboard/popup}}>
<$transclude $tiddler="$:/core/ui/ViewTemplate" $mode="block"/>
</$tiddler>
```

The overlay is `position: fixed` so it escapes the tile's `overflow` clipping and sits above every tile (whose `z-index` tops out at 9999 during a drag). The backdrop and the × button both clear the state tiddler to close. Because the state lives under `$:/state`, it is transient and never written to disk.

!! Division of labour

Everything except the pointer maths is wikitext and CSS: the cascade entry, the canvas body, the tile chrome, drop-to-add via the core `<$droppable>` widget, and the action strings that mutate tile fields. The widget is deliberately thin — it computes geometry and delegates all state writes back to wikitext.

</$fill>
